The same beasts were not accounted holy 82 in all parts of Egypt ; those which were worshipped in one part might be killed with impunity in another, as Herodotus ΙΙ, 69 expressly says in regard to the crocodiles; and according to Plutarch De Is. et Osir. c. 72 there was an idea that this difference had been designedly arranged by the old rulers to aid in dividing the people for the purpose of governing them more easily. Ibises and cats were equally sacred throughout the whole land, and a few other animals besides, which are enumerated in Strabo XVII, p. 812.
